                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d123">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.73/28½: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-25T13:00:00-03:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 25, 1920—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>39. Department’s telegram December 22nd, 4 p.m.<note n="97" xml:id="d123fn97">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_110">p. 110</ref>.</note>
                    Under date of May 24th Brazilian Minister for Foreign Affairs has informed this
                    Embassy in a written memorandum that the Pernambuco-Monrovia cable is not in
                    operation. The personnel of company were not molested and the cable equipment
                    was not seized [during the] war. For the moment at least it is not the intention
                    of the Brazilian Government to utilize this cable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morgan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
